On Nov 20, 2007, at 8:54 PM, Andy McKinley wrote:

> Does the Average Emissions for Passing Vehicles include all tested
> vehicles, or vehicles identical to the vehicle being tested?

The latter: average of vehicles in that age/weight category.

http://159.145.15.175/ftp/pdfdocs/asm_ave.pdf

> Overall, I'm very happy with the results, which are comparable with
> the results from last year's test. The only thing I question is the
> NO. How can I reduce this number?

Get the engine to the fountain of youth! You'll find that number  
climbs up over time.

You could try to richen the mixture a little and experiment but who  
is going to give you free time on their smog dyno?

> Have I
> been labeled "High Emitter Profile" because some PO didn't tune it up
> before going in for a test and badly failed?

I think so. It takes more than 1 fail with GP levels to warranty  
yearly testing.

Do a VIN search and see the smog history of your vehicle:

http://smogcheck.ca.gov/vehtests/pubtstqry.aspx

>  It's a real PITA; I can't renew my registration on line (have to go
> in and wait at the DMV)

Do you have an AAA membership? You can renew there.

> If so, how can I get that label removed?

> and I have the added inconvenience and expense
> of getting a smog test every year at a test only station.


Bureau of Automotive Repair (BAR) is part of the California  
Department of Consumer Affairs. Call them and see if there is recourse.

